Visualization of Fraud/Normal 's Transcation Amount¶

Undersampling¶

Because the data set is imbalanced, models will be not effecient if directly using imbalance data set.
Thus, here i use Undersampling technique to make training data balanced with ratio of 50:50

Percentage of normal transcations: 0.50
Percentage of fraud transcations: 0.50
Total number of transactions: 984

Split data¶

I will drop feature "Time" because it does not provide much usefulness.
Data is splitted into train and testing with ratio of 8:2
I will also center and scale X to make them have same scale.

After cleaning the data¶

After cleaning the data, it is better seperated by 2 classes. Even though there are some red dots mixed in blue area, it is understandable since these frauds are really difficult to detect as they are pretty much just like the normal transactions.

3. Part 2: Evaluation by different evaluation techniques¶

Back to top

In this research, I measure the accuracy by recall and precision scores. If i simply measure the overall accuracy, it lost its information of predicting fraud accuracy.
The overall accuracy would be 99.85% if i simply predict all labels to be 0 which is not i intend to do.
The most important accuracy is recall score and followed by precision. Recall measure the performance of TYPE 2 error. i want to high recall socre so that i miss as few as possible fraud transactions.
The second i measure is precision which is TYPE 1 error. It will send customers fraud alters for their normal transactions. i also want to this score high so i can minimize wrongful alters.

The best recall score i have from above models are Logistic Regression, both SVC, Decision Tree and Random Forest. They all have same recall score of 91%.
Next, I examine precision socre. Both SVC algorithms provide same high precision score of 98% while keep high recall score.
Thus, in this round, the SVC models are the best one to pick. It firstly use cross-validation to select the best parameter and apply to test set, which make its score convincible.

4.b) Bagging¶

Bagging is a technique to sampling training set with replacement. Most of time, the bagging method extract only 67% observations of the total. The rest of 32% will never appear in training which could left to be the testing set.

Here i use 6 algorithms using Bagging method to train the model and using the test set to see its final performance.

5.a) Adaboosting¶

An AdaBoost classifier is a meta-estimator that begins by fitting a classifier on the original dataset and then fits additional copies of the classifier on the same dataset but where the weights of incorrectly classified instances are adjusted such that subsequent classifiers focus more on difficult cases.

Here i use 3 different estimators applying to Adaboosting with different learning rates.
